To find the matrix that corresponds to rotating about the origin by an angle of $45^\circ$ clockwise, we can use the following steps:

1. Recall that the general formula for rotating a point $(x, y)$ about the origin by an angle $\theta$ counterclockwise is given by:
   \[
   \begin{bmatrix}
   \cos(\theta) & -\sin(\theta) \\
   \sin(\theta) & \cos(\theta) \\
   \end{bmatrix}
   \begin{bmatrix}
   x \\
   y \\
   \end{bmatrix}
   \]

2. Since we want to rotate clockwise, we need to negate the angle $\theta$. Therefore, we will use $\theta = -45^\circ$.

3. Substitute $\theta = -45^\circ$ into the formula from step 1:
   \[
   \begin{bmatrix}
   \cos(-45^\circ) & -\sin(-45^\circ) \\
   \sin(-45^\circ) & \cos(-45^\circ) \\
   \end{bmatrix}
   \begin{bmatrix}
   x \\
   y \\
   \end{bmatrix}
   \]

4. Simplify the trigonometric functions:
   \[
   \begin{bmatrix}
   \cos(-45^\circ) & -\sin(-45^\circ) \\
   \sin(-45^\circ) & \cos(-45^\circ) \\
   \end{bmatrix}
   \begin{bmatrix}
   x \\
   y \\
   \end{bmatrix}
   = \begin{bmatrix}
   \cos(45^\circ) & \sin(45^\circ) \\
   -\sin(45^\circ) & \cos(45^\circ) \\
   \end{bmatrix}
   \begin{bmatrix}
   x \\
   y \\
   \end{bmatrix}
   \]

5. Evaluate the trigonometric functions:
   \[
   \begin{bmatrix}
   \cos(45^\circ) & \sin(45^\circ) \\
   -\sin(45^\circ) & \cos(45^\circ) \\
   \end{bmatrix}
   \begin{bmatrix}
   x \\
   y \\
   \end{bmatrix}
   = \begin{bmatrix}
   \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} & \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \\
   -\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} & \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \\
   \end{bmatrix}
   \begin{bmatrix}
   x \\
   y \\
   \end{bmatrix}
   \]

6. The resulting matrix is the matrix that corresponds to rotating about the origin by an angle of $45^\circ$ clockwise.

Therefore, the matrix that corresponds to rotating about the origin by an angle of $45^\circ$ clockwise is:
\[
\begin{bmatrix}
\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} & \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \\
-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} & \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \\
\end{bmatrix}
\]

